{
  "id": "rj",
  "name": "RJ",
  "color": "#e8e4d8",
  "stage": "last-resort",
  "lore": {
    "tagline": "A well-defined living skeleton, standing head and clavicle above a miasma of screaming ghosts.",
    "personality": "A deadpan desert raconteur and ghost artist who talks like a dusty dictionary — obscure vocabulary, infinite patience, a BB gun, and a mini-excavator he rides like a horse. Adamant that he is not a golem, homunculus, or puppet coaxed to life by dark magic.",
    "backstory": "RJ builds the white sheet-ghost installations that haunt Bombay Beach, crowned by the World's Tallest Ghost over the Ghost Theater. He is an expert at everything from MS-DOS to snake-wrangling (in a strictly supervisory capacity, phone in hand). As the Biennale's gatekeeper he is the last door between a challenger and the Patron Prince — and when his patience runs out, the flesh goes and the skeleton answers."
  },
  "winQuotes": [
    "I know words like 'burgeomeister.' You knew none of them.",
    "I watched a man run MS-DOS from a crashing plane. This was less impressive.",
    "Get off my lot.",
    "You know nothing of bats."
  ],
  "vo": {
    "kiai": [
      "Go on, git!!!",
      "Hup!",
      "YAW!!!",
      "Hyah!",
      "Hyee-YAH!",
      "Whooooa."
    ],
    "hurt": [
      "Ngh!",
      "Dang.",
      "Rude.",
      "Ow, hell.",
      "Tsk.",
      "FUUUCK!!!"
    ],
    "victory": [
      "Get. Off. My. Lot.",
      "Well, I reckon that's that.",
      "The ghosts saw everything.",
      "Your problem is, you've got no style"
    ]
  },
  "arcade": {
    "motivation": "RJ doesn't care who wins the Biennale — he cares who tramples his lot getting there. Tao pays him in diesel and birdseed to watch the gate, and RJ watches it the way the desert watches everything: patiently, with a BB gun across his knees. Anyone who wants the Patron Prince answers to the gun, the ghosts, and the skeleton first.",
    "ending": "With Tao dethroned, RJ shrugs and gets back to work. There's a new ghost to raise — the tallest yet — and somebody left an art car axle-deep in the mud again. Bombay Beach never needed a champion. It needed a caretaker, and it always had one."
  },
